snippet.textDisplay:
Why is it that most (or all in my case) people that do these videos never mention the symbols when assembling a weapon?

There are slash/stab attack types.

A Large Blunt blade type will have a slash only attack type while a rapier handle will produce a stab only attack pattern. Mixing these 2 attack types and patterns will greatly reduce your damage with the assembled weapon. A dagger handle has both slash and stab attacks within its pattern so putting a slash or stab only blade on it will reduce the damage of the attack the blade is not suited for. 

Look for the symbols under attack types: =, ^, v to see how that blade fits on that handle.

Clarification: I just started the game I have picked up the first elemental weapon that deals electric damage and enjoy it.. snippet.textDisplay: Is it me or does it feel like you get locked into a blocking stance if you don't get a perfect parry? Then if the enemy has a quick follow up attack, you're less likely to get the next perfect parry...? That's what it feels like when you're fighting enemies that have rapid attack speeds, like some of the mini boss humans. The guy in Venigni's factory who is changing from the plague and needs to kill all puppets is a good example. I kept getting locked into blocking which led to a lot of frustration until I figured out how to side step him and get the rear reposte.

It just feels like a really lazy bloodborne / dark souls hybrid with all the same technical short comings.

The way the enemies perform very static death animations, then wobble around on the floor with the weight of a paper bag, it all just feels so dated to me.

Its upset me a bit because I was looking forward to this game since it was revealed YEARS AGO. Proper kick in the nuts.

snippet.textDisplay:
For those who didn't play the demo: The deflection works like Sekiro's, it doesn't disbalance the enemy for a riposte like in BB.

Standard block: recoverable hp loss (easy but costly)
Perfect guard: no hp loss and build enemy's nonvisible stagger meter. eg. When the Watchman boss does a chain attack, chain deflections are needed. 

This is the core part of the game and everything else is built around it. The nerfed roll during lock on is to encourage deflection.
